    <bioghist id="ref1" encodinganalog="545$a">
      <head>Historical Note</head>
      <p>The Norfolk and Western Railroad originated with the 1838 chartering of the City
                Point Railroad, a line between Petersburg and City Point, Virginia. The line was
                purchased by the South Side Railroad in 1854, which, in turn, merged with the
                Virginia &amp; Tennessee Railroad and the Norfolk &amp; Petersburg Railroad, forming
                the Atlantic, Mississippi &amp; Ohio Railroad in 1870. The AM&amp;O fell into
                bankruptcy and was purchased in 1881, the new owners incorporating under the name
                Norfolk and Western Railroad, with a line extending from Virginia's coast to
                Southwest Virginia. The N&amp;W went into receivership in 1895 and was reorganized
                as the Norfolk &amp; Western Railway the following year.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent id="ref9" encodinganalog="520$a">
      <head>Scope and Content</head>
      <p>This collection contains a set of accounting ledgers for the Norfolk and Western
                Railroad. The ledgers record the expenses of each of the company's several divisions
                (i.e., Clinch Valley, Durham, Kenova, Lynchburg, Norfolk, North Carolina,
                Pocahontas, Pulaski, Radford, Roanoke, Scioto Valley, Shenandoah and Winston-Salem).
                Included in each ledger are statements titled "accounts charged from vouchers"
                (changed to "detail of operating expenses for the month" in later volumes) for the
                individual divisions, followed by a sheet providing the system-wide totals. Also
                included are monthly summaries of accounts charged from vouchers payable, listing
                transactions by voucher number, with a breakdown of expenditures under various
                headings (general expenses, Commercial Department, maintenance of way, maintenance
                of engines, maintenance of cars, conducting transportation). A third set of sheets
                in each ledger appears to consist of the original account entries, listing
                individual voucher numbers and associated expenditures, again listed under the
                several different categories of expenses. Affixed to the inside covers of the
                ledgers are monthly statements titled "Amounts Charged Under 100 Year Mortgage from
                Vouchers," "Earnings and Expenses," "Percentages for Expenses Based on Car Mileage,"
                and "Analysis of Earnings and Expenses for the Month." At the end of the ledger set
                is a single volume, dated February 1895 and stamped "new acct." and bearing the
                names of the receivers, F. J. Kimball and Henry Fink.</p>
      <p>Also included in the collection are a set of ledgers specifically relating to the
                company's Scioto Valley Division, its records apparently having been kept separate
                from the remaining divisions from February 1895 forward. These ledgers contain the
                same type of accounting entries as those described above.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement id="ref3" encodinganalog="351">
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>The collection is arranged by ledger coverage area, then chronologically.</p>
